{"PageNumber":4,"Angle":0,"RotatedAngle":0,"Height":1620,"Width":2880,"OriginHeight":0,"OriginWidth":0,"Elements":[{"Index":0,"Type":"title","Text":"#  TCP Sequence Prediction","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":216,"Y":305},"LeftTop":{"X":216,"Y":185},"RightBottom":{"X":1527,"Y":305},"RightTop":{"X":1527,"Y":185}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":1,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"● A TCP sequence prediction attack attempts to guess an initial sequence number sent by the server at the start of a TCP session, so as to create a spoofed TCP session","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":219,"Y":707},"LeftTop":{"X":219,"Y":451},"RightBottom":{"X":2601,"Y":707},"RightTop":{"X":2601,"Y":451}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":2,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"● Early TCP stacks implemented sequence numbers by using a simple counter that was incremented by 1 with each transmission","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":219,"Y":916},"LeftTop":{"X":219,"Y":749},"RightBottom":{"X":2561,"Y":916},"RightTop":{"X":2561,"Y":749}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":3,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"● Without using any randomness, it was trivial to predict the next sequence number, which is the key to this attack","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":219,"Y":1133},"LeftTop":{"X":219,"Y":963},"RightBottom":{"X":2443,"Y":1133},"RightTop":{"X":2443,"Y":963}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":4,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"● Modern TCP stack implementations use pseudo-random number generators to determine sequence numbers, which makes a TCP sequence prediction attack more difficult, but not impossible","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":219,"Y":1431},"LeftTop":{"X":219,"Y":1177},"RightBottom":{"X":2480,"Y":1431},"RightTop":{"X":2480,"Y":1177}},"InsetImageName":"","Ele